4645/* The following code discovers opportunities to switch a memory reference
4646 and an increment by modifying the address. We ensure that this is done
4647 only for dependencies that are only used to show a single register
4648 dependence (using DEP_NONREG and DEP_MULTIPLE), and so that every memory
4649 instruction involved is subject to only one dep that can cause a pattern
4650 change.
4651
4652 When we discover a suitable dependency, we fill in the dep_replacement
4653 structure to show how to modify the memory reference. */
4654
4655/* Holds information about a pair of memory reference and register increment
4656 insns which depend on each other, but could possibly be interchanged. */
4657struct mem_inc_info
4658{
4659 rtx_insn *inc_insn;
4660 rtx_insn *mem_insn;
4661
4662 rtx *mem_loc;
4663 /* A register occurring in the memory address for which we wish to break
4664 the dependence. This must be identical to the destination register of
4665 the increment. */
4666 rtx mem_reg0;
4667 /* Any kind of index that is added to that register. */
4668 rtx mem_index;
4669 /* The constant offset used in the memory address. */
4670 HOST_WIDE_INT mem_constant;
4671 /* The constant added in the increment insn. Negated if the increment is
4672 after the memory address. */
4673 HOST_WIDE_INT inc_constant;
4674 /* The source register used in the increment. May be different from mem_reg0
4675 if the increment occurs before the memory address. */
4676 rtx inc_input;
4677};
4678
4679/* Verify that the memory location described in MII can be replaced with
4680 one using NEW_ADDR. Return the new memory reference or NULL_RTX. The
4681 insn remains unchanged by this function. */
4682
4683static rtx
4684attempt_change (struct mem_inc_info *mii, rtx new_addr)
4685{
4686 rtx mem = *mii->mem_loc;
4687 rtx new_mem;
4688
4689 /* Jump through a lot of hoops to keep the attributes up to date. We
4690 do not want to call one of the change address variants that take
4691 an offset even though we know the offset in many cases. These
4692 assume you are changing where the address is pointing by the
4693 offset. */
4694 new_mem = replace_equiv_address_nv (mem, new_addr);
4695 if (! validate_change (mii->mem_insn, mii->mem_loc, new_mem, 0))
4696 {
4697 if (sched_verbose >= 5)
4698 fprintf (sched_dump, "validation failure\n");
4699 return NULL_RTX;
4700 }
4701
4702 /* Put back the old one. */
4703 validate_change (mii->mem_insn, mii->mem_loc, mem, 0);
4704
4705 return new_mem;
4706}
4707
4708/* Return true if INSN is of a form "a = b op c" where a and b are
4709 regs. op is + if c is a reg and +|- if c is a const. Fill in
4710 informantion in MII about what is found.
4711 BEFORE_MEM indicates whether the increment is found before or after
4712 a corresponding memory reference. */
4713
4714static bool
4715parse_add_or_inc (struct mem_inc_info *mii, rtx_insn *insn, bool before_mem)
4716{
4717 rtx pat = single_set (insn);
4718 rtx src, cst;
4719 bool regs_equal;
4720
4721 if (RTX_FRAME_RELATED_P (insn) || !pat)
4722 return false;
4723
4724 /* Result must be single reg. */
4725 if (!REG_P (SET_DEST (pat)))
4726 return false;
4727
4728 if (GET_CODE (SET_SRC (pat)) != PLUS)
4729 return false;
4730
4731 mii->inc_insn = insn;
4732 src = SET_SRC (pat);
4733 mii->inc_input = XEXP (src, 0);
4734
4735 if (!REG_P (XEXP (src, 0)))
4736 return false;
4737
4738 if (!rtx_equal_p (SET_DEST (pat), mii->mem_reg0))
4739 return false;
4740
4741 cst = XEXP (src, 1);
4742 if (!CONST_INT_P (cst))
4743 return false;
4744 mii->inc_constant = INTVAL (cst);
4745
4746 regs_equal = rtx_equal_p (mii->inc_input, mii->mem_reg0);
4747
4748 if (!before_mem)
4749 {
4750 mii->inc_constant = -mii->inc_constant;
4751 if (!regs_equal)
4752 return false;
4753 }
4754
4755 if (regs_equal && REGNO (SET_DEST (pat)) == STACK_POINTER_REGNUM)
4756 {
4757 /* Note that the sign has already been reversed for !before_mem. */
4758 if (STACK_GROWS_DOWNWARD)
4759 return mii->inc_constant > 0;
4760 else
4761 return mii->inc_constant < 0;
4762 }
4763 return true;
4764}
4765
4766/* Once a suitable mem reference has been found and the corresponding data
4767 in MII has been filled in, this function is called to find a suitable
4768 add or inc insn involving the register we found in the memory
4769 reference. */
4770
4771static bool
4772find_inc (struct mem_inc_info *mii, bool backwards)
4773{
4774 sd_iterator_def sd_it;
4775 dep_t dep;
4776
4777 sd_it = sd_iterator_start (mii->mem_insn,
4778 backwards ? SD_LIST_HARD_BACK : SD_LIST_FORW);
4779 while (sd_iterator_cond (&sd_it, &dep))
4780 {
4781 dep_node_t node = DEP_LINK_NODE (*sd_it.linkp);
4782 rtx_insn *pro = DEP_PRO (dep);
4783 rtx_insn *con = DEP_CON (dep);
4784 rtx_insn *inc_cand = backwards ? pro : con;
4785 if (DEP_NONREG (dep) || DEP_MULTIPLE (dep))
4786 goto next;
4787 if (parse_add_or_inc (mii, inc_cand, backwards))
4788 {
4789 struct dep_replacement *desc;
4790 df_ref def;
4791 rtx newaddr, newmem;
4792
4793 if (sched_verbose >= 5)
4794 fprintf (sched_dump, "candidate mem/inc pair: %d %d\n",
4795 INSN_UID (mii->mem_insn), INSN_UID (inc_cand));
4796
4797 /* Need to assure that none of the operands of the inc
4798 instruction are assigned to by the mem insn. */
4799 FOR_EACH_INSN_DEF (def, mii->mem_insn)
4800 if (reg_overlap_mentioned_p (DF_REF_REG (def), mii->inc_input)
4801 || reg_overlap_mentioned_p (DF_REF_REG (def), mii->mem_reg0))
4802 {
4803 if (sched_verbose >= 5)
4804 fprintf (sched_dump,
4805 "inc conflicts with store failure.\n");
4806 goto next;
4807 }
4808
4809 newaddr = mii->inc_input;
4810 if (mii->mem_index != NULL_RTX)
4811 newaddr = gen_rtx_PLUS (GET_MODE (newaddr), newaddr,
4812 mii->mem_index);
4813 newaddr = plus_constant (GET_MODE (newaddr), newaddr,
4814 mii->mem_constant + mii->inc_constant);
4815 newmem = attempt_change (mii, newaddr);
4816 if (newmem == NULL_RTX)
4817 goto next;
4818 if (sched_verbose >= 5)
4819 fprintf (sched_dump, "successful address replacement\n");
4820 desc = XCNEW (struct dep_replacement);
4821 DEP_REPLACE (dep) = desc;
4822 desc->loc = mii->mem_loc;
4823 desc->newval = newmem;
4824 desc->orig = *desc->loc;
4825 desc->insn = mii->mem_insn;
4826 move_dep_link (DEP_NODE_BACK (node), INSN_HARD_BACK_DEPS (con),
4827 INSN_SPEC_BACK_DEPS (con));
4828 if (backwards)
4829 {
4830 FOR_EACH_DEP (mii->inc_insn, SD_LIST_BACK, sd_it, dep)
4831 add_dependence_1 (mii->mem_insn, DEP_PRO (dep),
4832 REG_DEP_TRUE);
4833 }
4834 else
4835 {
4836 FOR_EACH_DEP (mii->inc_insn, SD_LIST_FORW, sd_it, dep)
4837 add_dependence_1 (DEP_CON (dep), mii->mem_insn,
4838 REG_DEP_ANTI);
4839 }
4840 return true;
4841 }
4842 next:
4843 sd_iterator_next (&sd_it);
4844 }
4845 return false;
4846}
4847
4848/* A recursive function that walks ADDRESS_OF_X to find memory references
4849 which could be modified during scheduling. We call find_inc for each
4850 one we find that has a recognizable form. MII holds information about
4851 the pair of memory/increment instructions.
4852 We ensure that every instruction with a memory reference (which will be
4853 the location of the replacement) is assigned at most one breakable
4854 dependency. */
4855
4856static bool
4857find_mem (struct mem_inc_info *mii, rtx *address_of_x)
4858{
4859 rtx x = *address_of_x;
4860 enum rtx_code code = GET_CODE (x);
4861 const char *const fmt = GET_RTX_FORMAT (code);
4862 int i;
4863
4864 if (code == MEM)
4865 {
4866 rtx reg0 = XEXP (x, 0);
4867
4868 mii->mem_loc = address_of_x;
4869 mii->mem_index = NULL_RTX;
4870 mii->mem_constant = 0;
4871 if (GET_CODE (reg0) == PLUS && CONST_INT_P (XEXP (reg0, 1)))
4872 {
4873 mii->mem_constant = INTVAL (XEXP (reg0, 1));
4874 reg0 = XEXP (reg0, 0);
4875 }
4876 if (GET_CODE (reg0) == PLUS)
4877 {
4878 mii->mem_index = XEXP (reg0, 1);
4879 reg0 = XEXP (reg0, 0);
4880 }
4881 if (REG_P (reg0))
4882 {
4883 df_ref use;
4884 int occurrences = 0;
4885
4886 /* Make sure this reg appears only once in this insn. Can't use
4887 count_occurrences since that only works for pseudos. */
4888 FOR_EACH_INSN_USE (use, mii->mem_insn)
4889 if (reg_overlap_mentioned_p (reg0, DF_REF_REG (use)))
4890 if (++occurrences > 1)
4891 {
4892 if (sched_verbose >= 5)
4893 fprintf (sched_dump, "mem count failure\n");
4894 return false;
4895 }
4896
4897 mii->mem_reg0 = reg0;
4898 return find_inc (mii, true) || find_inc (mii, false);
4899 }
4900 return false;
4901 }
4902
4903 if (code == SIGN_EXTRACT || code == ZERO_EXTRACT)
4904 {
4905 /* If REG occurs inside a MEM used in a bit-field reference,
4906 that is unacceptable. */
4907 return false;
4908 }
4909
4910 /* Time for some deep diving. */
4911 for (i = GET_RTX_LENGTH (code) - 1; i >= 0; i--)
4912 {
4913 if (fmt[i] == 'e')
4914 {
4915 if (find_mem (mii, &XEXP (x, i)))
4916 return true;
4917 }
4918 else if (fmt[i] == 'E')
4919 {
4920 int j;
4921 for (j = XVECLEN (x, i) - 1; j >= 0; j--)
4922 if (find_mem (mii, &XVECEXP (x, i, j)))
4923 return true;
4924 }
4925 }
4926 return false;
4927}
4928
4929
4930/* Examine the instructions between HEAD and TAIL and try to find
4931 dependencies that can be broken by modifying one of the patterns. */
4932
4933void
4934find_modifiable_mems (rtx_insn *head, rtx_insn *tail)
4935{
4936 rtx_insn *insn, *next_tail = NEXT_INSN (tail);
4937 int success_in_block = 0;
4938
4939 for (insn = head; insn != next_tail; insn = NEXT_INSN (insn))
4940 {
4941 struct mem_inc_info mii;
4942
4943 if (!NONDEBUG_INSN_P (insn) || RTX_FRAME_RELATED_P (insn))
4944 continue;
4945
4946 mii.mem_insn = insn;
4947 if (find_mem (&mii, &PATTERN (insn)))
4948 success_in_block++;
4949 }
4950 if (success_in_block && sched_verbose >= 5)
4951 fprintf (sched_dump, "%d candidates for address modification found.\n",
4952 success_in_block);
4953}
